    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For a larger number of stops, the **nearest-neighbor** heuristic is indeed a quick fix, but it can get stuck in a local optimum and miss the truly best path. The more advanced approach is to use **dynamic programming** (specifically the **Held–Karp algorithm**) or a **genetic algorithm** if you want to explore a much larger search space. The Held–Karp method computes the optimal solution by evaluating all possible sub-routes, using a recurrence relation that keeps track of the minimum cost to reach each stop while maintaining a visited set. For 12 stops, this is still computationally feasible and will give you a near-perfect route. If you were dealing with hundreds of stops, you might switch to a genetic algorithm or a simulated annealing approach, which iteratively mutate and select routes to converge on a global optimum.",
      "source": "target",
